<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-219-293 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 370 108</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 18 1991 v25 n7 p68(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Managing IS in Hawaii is no vacation. (problems faced byinformation systems managers in Hawaii)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bozman, Jean S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Managers of information systems (IS) shops in Hawaii face specialproblems due to their distance from the US mainland and the largetime difference.andP;  Technical publications take two weeks to arrive,and attending conferences is difficult and costly.andP;  The cost ofliving in Hawaii is extremely high, but many employers believethey can pay less than the national average because the islandclimate is an inherent benefit.andP;  Technology nevertheless helpsHawaiians in their relative isolation, because technical supportcan be obtained over the telephone.andP;  Nearly all Hawaiian IS jobsare on the island of Oahu, because banks, hotels and othercomputer users center their operations in Honolulu.andP;  Manycomputers are not state-of-the art; aging IBM 4300 and DEC VAX11/785s remain in widespread sue.andP;  The Hawaiian IS community isvery close, and news of how well a vendor performs a job spreadsrapidly.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     HawaiiManagement of EDPUser NeedsComputer industryMIS.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>